   Alfred Piergallini | Gerber Products Company | ZoomInfo.com


Alfred A. Piergallini, Gerber Products Co. Freed Of Non-performers, Gerber Rebounds - tribunedigital-mcall






 


 Home→CollectionsAlfred A. Piergallini, Gerber Products Co. Freed Of Non-performers, Gerber ReboundsEXECUTIVE INTERVIEWMay 27, 1991|by CONSTANCE WALKER, The Morning Call"We got in the car at the hospital -- I'll never forget this. We were in Cincinnati and the nurse handed my wife this kid, our newborn daughter. So I'm driving away and I looked at my wife and said, `Now, you know how to take care of this kid, don't you?' She said, `I haven't the slightest idea.'"Alfred A. Piergallini, a native of Easton, tells the story with a hearty laugh. It seems incongruous that this man, who admittedly once thought baby care was a genetic inheritance, now runs the company that is synonymous with babies -- Gerber Products Co.Piergallini became chairman of the board, chief executive officer and president of the Michigan-based company at the turn of the year in 1990 following David Johnson, who left to head Campbell Soup Co.The food industry was not new to Piergallini; he had worked at Sara Lee Corp. and Carnation Co. By then, babies also were not new; he has a 16-year-old daughter and 14-year-old son.Now the challenge was to continue what Johnson started -- helping Gerber Products gain back what it lost in the 1980s because of overdiversification -- and preparing the company for the future, including expanding the product menu and the company's geographical reaches in the face of strong competition by corporation giants such as Philip Morris Cos., Nestle S.A. and H.J. Heinz Co.During the last fiscal year, which ended March 31, Gerber had total sales of about $1.2 billion -- food, baby-care items, apparel and life insurance -- and captured 70.3 percent of the total baby-food market.Recently, while visiting Easton Area High School -- where he graduated in 1964 -- Piergallini talked about changes in Gerber Products, trends in the baby-care industry and his philosophy of business.Question: What kind of trends are you experiencing in the baby-food industry and how does that play into Gerber's plans?Piergallini: Our mission for the total company is in the feeding, caring and clothing children from zero to about 3 years of age. We want to dominate that category with Gerber products.The trends in our business are driven by birth rates. The birth rate nationally is up about 3.9 percent, about 4 million births a year, give or take a few.We entered the baby-formula business about 18 months ago. That came about because of our mission and that starts with the formula. We believe breast-feeding is the best way to take care of babies. But if you can't breast feed, or in some cases women supplement breast-feeding, we want you to try Gerber.A trend that negatively affected us is the early substitution of table foods when mom decides the kid should eat mashed potatoes and Spaghetti-Os. But none of those foods are formulated for that age group. Research tells us mother uses that because it's convenient, but it has high sodium, high fat and a lot of sugar.So, what we're doing is trying to extend the consumption cycle by developing a toddler transitional food category -- Gerber Graduates. This would carry us from the 11-month-old up to about 36 months. We recently started rolling out the main meals -- the first element in that toddler category. We're hopeful that, by the end of this fiscal year, we'll have a whole series under the Gerber Graduates name that might include snacks, side dishes and juices.There's a big amount of consumption beyond 11 months that we're not really taking advantage of now because when mothers give up baby food, they give up us.Q: How has the shift in environmental awareness affected Gerber?Piergallini: The nutrition and environmental consciousness is all in our favor. The trend in the U.S. is going back to cloth diapers because of the environmental push. We are the largest cloth diaper manufacturer in the United States. The issue we are facing now is strong imports and they are tough to fight because of the price is so much lower -- we make all of our diapers domestically.We've got a great new diaper we just developed called "The Easy One" for newborns. It's with velcro straps; no pins. We're testing it in a number of hospitals. But one thing we will never be able to beat in disposables -- and they are a good product -- is convenience.Q: Is there a problem with marketing cloth diapers since the women having babies now probably have never used cloth diapers before and don't know how?Piergallini: Most people don't know how to use (cloth diapers). They'd like to, but they think it's going to be really difficult and it isn't. That's why we've recently come out with a diaper kit -- two dozen diapers, pins, diaper liners, vinyl pants, diaper cover and a video tape.The tape shows how to take care of the baby, but the whole idea was `Here's how you use cloth diapers; here's how you fold them; here's how you put them on the kid.' It even gives you the different folds for the girl and boy. It costs about $25, but you go home, open it up and you can do it.Q: More and more companies are looking beyond U.S. borders to global markets. What is Gerber doing to go beyond?1 | 2 |  Next


