New Gerber President Called Sound Manager


By PAUL C. JUDGE, Special to The New York Times


Published: January 4, 1990









DETROIT, Jan. 3— 
                    Alfred A. Piergallini today was named president and chief executive of the Gerber Products Company, succeeding David W. Johnson, who will take the top posts at the Campbell Soup Company.        

                    Mr. Piergallini, who had been chief operating officer, has been with the baby-food concern for only nine months. Yet his relative inexperience is hardly a drawback at Gerber, where a thorough restructuring by the departing chief executive, Mr. Johnson, changed the corporate culture and turned the company around in two years.        

                    Unlike his predecessor, Mr. Piergallini is largely unknown outside the company, but has built a solid reputation managing Gerber's operations.        

                    ''That's what Gerber needs right now, a strong operations guy,'' said Kurt A. Feuerman, an analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert.        

                    Renewed Focus on Baby Food        

                    Mr. Piergallini, who is 43 years old, inherits a company that is prospering. A renewed focus on baby food pushed earnings up 32 percent, to $53.3 million, in the first six months of the 1989 fiscal year. Analysts say Gerber is on track to earn about $2.75 a share when its fiscal year ends in March, compared with $2.17 last year.        

                    Mr. Piergallini joined Gerber, based in Fremont, Mich., after working for a variety of consumer-products concerns. Most recently he was senior vice president of the Carnation Company. He came to Mr. Johnson's attention after expanding Carnation's market share in pet food.        

                    When he was hired at Gerber in April, those familiar with the company expected him to succeed Mr. Johnson eventually. But the change in leadership came sooner than some had expected, despite rumors that Mr. Johnson was considering an offer from Campbell.        

                    Mr. Piergallini, who said his management philosophy is ''identical'' to Mr. Johnson's, will not tinker with the profit machine that Mr. Johnson has created at Gerber. Instead, he emphasized his plans to follow through on the divestitures that began under Mr. Johnson, and said he hoped to squeeze even more profit from the baby food business through wider distribution and some new food products, including a line of milk-based baby formula.        

                    Criticism of Advertisements        

                    The American Academy of Pediatricians has criticized Gerber for aiming at consumers rather than doctors with advertisements for its new line of baby formula, which became available last summer. The pediatricians have said Gerber's advertising campaign undermines their efforts to encourage breast-feeding.        

                    Mr. Piergallini said the opposition to the marketing strategy ''has not appeared to adversely affect the introduction of our formula product.''        

                    The company is under pressure to establish its milk-based formula, which is manufactured by the Bristol-Myers Squibb Company and sold by Gerber under a joint agreement. Gerber tried to enter the market in 1967 with a formula called Modilac, but it was discontinued in 1972.        

                    The company expects profits from its new formula to be about $1 million to $4 million annually by 1992. To accomplish that, Gerber will have to raise the price of the formula by 6 to 7 percent each year, said William Maguire, an analyst for Merrill Lynch.        

                    Sale of Day-Care Centers        

                    Mr. Piergallini said his first job was to complete the sale of a national chain of day-care centers, which he acknowledges ''will not realize any significant gain'' for Gerber. He also intends to follow through on the company's plans, announced in November, to close a baby food plant in Niagara Falls, Ontario.        

                    Some Wall Street analysts have alerted investors to sell their Gerber shares, believing that the company can go no higher without Mr. Johnson as its guide. But other analysts familiar with the company suggested that Gerber still had potential to grow.        

                    ''The simple fact that Al Piergallini is in charge does not reduce Gerber's earnings,'' Mr. Maguire said.        

                    Gerber stock fell 62.5 cents yesterday, to $46.75, in trading on the New York Stock Exchange.        

                    photo: Alfred A. Piergallini, the new president and chief executive of the Gerber Products Company.        








 














 
























 








 

